#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:9
msgid ""
"Crates.io has many useful libraries for a variety of purposes, but it's "
"difficult to find which crates are meant for a particular purpose and then "
"to decide among the available crates which one is most suitable in a "
"particular context. [Categorization](https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io/"
"pull/473) and [badges](https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io/pull/481) are "
"coming to crates.io; categories help with finding a set of crates to "
"consider and badges help communicate attributes of crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:16
msgid ""
"**This RFC aims to create a default ranking of crates within a list of "
"crates that have a category or keyword in order to make a recommendation to "
"crate users about which crates are likely to deserve further manual "
"evaluation.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:23
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:26
msgid ""
"Finding and evaluating crates can be time consuming. People already familiar "
"with the Rust ecosystem often know which crates are best for which puproses, "
"but we want to share that knowledge with everyone. For example, someone "
"looking for a crate to help create a parser should be able to navigate to a "
"category for that purpose and get a list of crates to consider. This list "
"would include crates such as [nom](https://crates.io/crates/nom) and "
"[peresil](https://crates.io/crates/peresil), and the order in which they "
"appear should be significant and should help make the decision between the "
"crates in this category easier."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:38
msgid ""
"This helps address the goal of \"Rust should provide easy access to high "
"quality crates\" as stated in the [Rust 2017 Roadmap](https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/rfcs/pull/1774)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:43
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:46
msgid ""
"Please see the [Appendix: Comparative Research](#appendix-comparative-"
"research) section for ways that other package manager websites have solved "
"this problem, and the [Appendix: User Research](#appendix-user-research) "
"section for results of a user research survey we did on how people evaluate "
"crates by hand today."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:51
msgid "A few assumptions we made:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:53
msgid ""
"Measures that can be made automatically are preferred over measures that "
"would need administrators, curators, or the community to spend time on "
"manually."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:56
msgid ""
"Measures that can be made for any crate regardless of that crate's choice of "
"version control, repository host, or CI service are preferred over measures "
"that would only be available or would be more easily available with git, "
"GitHub, Travis, and Appveyor. Our thinking is that when this additional "
"information is available, it would be better to display a badge indicating "
"it since this is valuable information, but it should not influence the "
"ranking of the crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:63
msgid ""
"There are some measures, like \"suitability for the current task\" or "
"\"whether I like the way the crate is implemented\" that crates.io shouldn't "
"even attempt to assess, since those could potentially differ across "
"situations for the same person looking for a crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:67
msgid ""
"We assume we will be able to calculate these in a reasonable amount of time "
"either on-demand or by a background job initiated on crate publish and saved "
"in the database as appropriate. We think the measures we have proposed can "
"be done without impacting the performance of either publishing or browsing "
"crates noticeably. If this does not turn out to be the case, we will have to "
"adjust the formula."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:74
msgid "Order by recent downloads"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:76
msgid ""
"Through the iterations of this RFC, there was no consensus around a way to "
"order crates that would be useful, understandable, resistant to being gamed, "
"and not require work of curators, reviewers, or moderators. Furthermore, "
"different people in different situations may value different aspects of "
"crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:81
msgid ""
"Instead of attempting to order crates as a majority of people would rank "
"them, we propose a coarser measure to expose the set of crates worthy of "
"further consideration on the first page of a category or keyword. At that "
"point, the person looking for a crate can use other indicators on the page "
"to decide which crates best meet their needs."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:87
msgid ""
"**The default ordering of crates within a keyword or category will be "
"changed to be the number of downloads in the last 90 days.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:90
msgid ""
"While coarse, downloads show how many people or other crates have found this "
"crate to be worthy of using. By limiting to the last 90 days, crates that "
"have been around the longest won't have an advantage over new crates that "
"might be better. Crates that are lower in the \"stack\", such as `libc`, "
"will always have a higher number of downloads than those higher in the stack "
"due to the number of crates using a lower-level crate as a dependency. "
"Within a category or keyword, however, crates are likely to be from the same "
"level of the stack and thus their download numbers will be comparable."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:99
msgid ""
"Crates are currently ordered by all-time downloads and the sort option "
"button says \"Downloads\". We will:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:102
msgid "change the ordering to be downloads in the last 90 days"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:103
msgid ""
"change the number of downloads displayed with each crate to be those made in "
"the last 90 days"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:105
msgid "change the sort option button to say \"Recent Downloads\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:107
msgid ""
"\"All-time Downloads\" could become another sort option in the menu, "
"alongside \"Alphabetical\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:110
msgid "Add more badges, filters, and sorting options"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:112
msgid ""
"Crates.io now has badges for master branch CI status, and [will soon have a "
"badge indicating the version(s) of Rust a particular version builds "
"successfully on](https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io/pull/540)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:118
msgid ""
"To enable a person to narrow down relevant crates to find the one that will "
"best meet their needs, we will add more badges and indicators. **Badges will "
"not influence crate ordering**."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:122
msgid ""
"Some badges may require use of third-party services such as GitHub. We "
"recognize that not everyone uses these services, but note a specific badge "
"is only one factor that people can consider out of many."
msgstr ""

