"discussing documentation was the desire to quickly find an example of how to "
"use the crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:144
msgid "This would be addressed in two ways."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:146
msgid "Render README on a crate's page"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:148
msgid ""
"[Render README files on a crate's page on crates.io](https://github.com/rust-"
"lang/crates.io/issues/81) so that people can quickly see for themselves the "
"information that a crate author chooses to make available in their README. "
"We can nudge towards having an example in the README by adding a template "
"README that includes an Examples section [in what `cargo new` generates]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/issues/3506)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:157
msgid "\"Well Documented\" badge"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:159
msgid ""
"For each crate published, in a background job, unpack the crate files and "
"calculate the ratio of lines of documentation to lines of code as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:162
msgid ""
"Find the number of lines of documentation in Rust files: `grep -r \"//[!/]\" "
"--binary-files=without-match --include=*.rs . | wc -l`"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:164
msgid "Find the number of lines in the README file, if specified in Cargo.toml"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:165
msgid ""
"Find the number of lines in Rust files: `find . -name '*.rs' | xargs wc -l`"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:167
msgid ""
"We would then add the lines in the README to the lines of documentation, "
"subtract the lines of documentation from the total lines of code, and divide "
"the lines of documentation by the lines of non-documentation in order to get "
"the ratio of documentation to code. Test code (and any documentation within "
"test code) _is_ part of this calculation."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:173
msgid ""
"Any crate getting in the top 20% of all crates would get a badge saying "
"\"well documented\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:176
msgid ""
"This measure is gameable if a crate adds many lines that match the "
"documentation regex but don't provide meaningful content, such as `/// lol`. "
"While this may be easy to implement, a person looking at the documentation "
"for a crate using this technique would immediately be able to see that the "
"author is trying to game the system and reject it. If this becomes a common "
"problem, we can re-evaluate this situation, but we believe the community of "
"crate authors genuinely want to provide great documentation to crate users. "
"We want to encourage and reward well-documented crates, and this outweighs "
"the risk of potential gaming of the system."
msgstr ""

