#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:703
msgid ""
"Ok, this one isn't from the survey, it's from [a Sept 2015 internals thread]"
"(https://users.rust-lang.org/t/lets-talk-about-ecosystem-"
"documentation/2791/24?u=carols10cents):"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:707
msgid ""
"there should be indicator in Crates.io that show how much code is "
"documented, this would help with choosing well done package."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:710
msgid ""
"I really love this idea! Showing a percentage or a little progress bar next "
"to each crate with the proportion of public items with at least some docs "
"would be a great starting point."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:716
msgid ""
"On nom's crates.io page I checked the version (2.0.0) and when the latest "
"version came out (less than a month ago). I know that versioning is "
"inconsistent across crates, but I'm reassured when a crate has V >= 1.0 "
"because it typically indicates that the authors are confident the crate is "
"production-ready. I also like to see multiple, relatively-recent releases "
"because it signals the authors are serious about maintenance."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:725
msgid ""
"Answering yes scores points:  crates.io page:  Does the crate have a major "
"version >= 1?  Has there been a release recently, and maybe even a steady "
"stream of minor or patch-level releases?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:731
msgid "From github:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:732
msgid ""
"Number of commits and of contributors (A small number of commits (\\< 100) "
"and of contributors (\\< 3) is often the sign of a personal project, "
"probably not very much used except by its author. All other things equal, I "
"tend to prefer active projects.);"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:740
msgid "Tests:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:741
msgid "Is critical functionality well tested?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:742
msgid "Is the entire package well tested?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:743
msgid "Are the tests clear and descriptive?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:744
msgid "Could I reimplement the library based on these tests?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:745
msgid "Does the project have CI?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:746
msgid "Is master green?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:748
msgid "Popularity/credibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:750
msgid ""
"I look  at the number of download. If it is too small (~ \\<1000), I assume "
"the crate has not yet reached a good quality. nom catches my attention "
"because it has 200K download: I assume it is a high quality crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:756
msgid ""
"Compare the number of downloads: More downloads = more popular = should be "
"the best"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:761
msgid ""
"Popularity:  - Although not being a huge factor, it can help tip the scale "
"when one is more popular or well supported than another when all other "
"factors are close."
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:765
msgid "Overall"
msgstr ""

#: src/1824-crates.io-default-ranking.md:767
msgid ""
"I can't pick a most important trait because certain ones outweigh others "
"when combined, etc. I.e. number of downloads is OK, but may only suggest "
"that it's been around the longest. Same with number of dependent crates "
"(which probably spikes number of downloads). I like a crate that is well "
"documented, has a large user base (# dependent crates + downloads + stars), "
"is post 1.0, is active (i.e. a release within the past 6 months?), and it "
"helps when it's a prominent author (but that I feel is an unfair metric)."
msgstr ""

